## Sometimes you might need to babysit your respondents




::: {.cell output-location='fragment'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="|2-8|9"}
cat_lovers |>
  mutate(
    number_of_cats = case_when(
      name == "Ginger Clark" ~ 2,
      name == "Doug Bass"    ~ 3,
      .default = as.numeric(number_of_cats)
      )
    ) |>
  summarize(mean_cats = mean(number_of_cats))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
Warning: There was 1 warning in `mutate()`.
ℹ In argument: `number_of_cats = case_when(...)`.
Caused by warning in `vec_case_when()`:
! NAs introduced by coercion
```


:::

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  mean_cats
      <dbl>
1     0.833
```


:::
:::




## Always you need to respect data types




::: {.cell output-location='fragment'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-line-numbers="|4-6|8|10"}
cat_lovers |>#| 
  mutate(
    number_of_cats = case_when(
      name == "Ginger Clark" ~ "2",
      name == "Doug Bass"    ~ "3",
      .default = number_of_cats
      ),
    number_of_cats = as.numeric(number_of_cats)
    ) |>
  summarize(mean_cats = mean(number_of_cats))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  mean_cats
      <dbl>
1     0.833
```


:::
:::




## Moral of the story

- If your data does not behave how you expect it to, type coercion upon reading in the data might be the reason.
- Go in and investigate your data, apply the fix, *save your data*, live happily ever after.

# Data types

## Data types in R

- **logical**
- **double**
- **integer**
- **character**
- and some more, but we won't be focusing on those

## Logical & character

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="35%"}
**logical** - boolean values `TRUE` and `FALSE`

<br>




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(TRUE)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "logical"
```


:::
:::



:::

::: {.column width="35%" .fragment}
**character** - character strings

<br>
<br>




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof("hello")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "character"
```


:::
:::



:::

::::

## Double & integer

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="35%"}
**double** - floating point numerical values (default numerical type)

<br>




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(1.335)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "double"
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(7)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "double"
```


:::
:::



:::

::: {.column width="35%" .fragment}
**integer** - integer numerical values (indicated with an `L`)

<br>




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(7L)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "integer"
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(1:3)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "integer"
```


:::
:::



:::

::::

## Concatenation

Vectors can be constructed using the `c()` function.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(1, 2, 3)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 1 2 3
```


:::
:::




. . .



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c("Hello", "World!")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "Hello"  "World!"
```


:::
:::




. . .




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(c("hi", "hello"), c("bye", "jello"))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "hi"    "hello" "bye"   "jello"
```


:::
:::




## Converting between types

::: hand
with intention...
:::

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="35%"}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- 1:3
x
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 1 2 3
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(x)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "integer"
```


:::
:::



:::

::: {.column width="35%" .fragment}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
y <- as.character(x)
y
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "1" "2" "3"
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(y)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "character"
```


:::
:::



:::

::::

## Converting between types

::: hand
with intention...
:::

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="35%"}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
x <- c(TRUE, FALSE)
x
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1]  TRUE FALSE
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(x)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "logical"
```


:::
:::



:::

::: {.column width="35%" .fragment}



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
y <- as.numeric(x)
y
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 1 0
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
typeof(y)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "double"
```


:::
:::



:::

::::

## Converting between types

::: hand
without intention...
:::




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(1, "Hello")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "1"     "Hello"
```


:::
:::




. . .

R will happily convert between various types without complaint when different types of data are concatenated in a vector, and that's not always a great thing!

. . .




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(FALSE, 3L)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0 3
```


:::
:::



. . .




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(1.2, 3L)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 1.2 3.0
```


:::
:::




. . .




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
c(2L, "two")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] "2"   "two"
```


:::
:::




## Explicit vs. implicit coercion

Let's give formal names to what we've seen so far:

::: incremental
- **Explicit coercion** is when you call a function like `as.logical()`, `as.numeric()`, `as.integer()`, `as.double()`, or `as.character()`

- **Implicit coercion** happens when you use a vector in a specific context that expects a certain type of vector
:::

# Special values

## Special values

- `NA`: Not available

. . .

- `NaN`: Not a number




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
0 / 0
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] NaN
```


:::
:::




. . .

- `Inf`: Positive infinity




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
pi / 0
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] Inf
```


:::
:::




. . .

- `-Inf`: Negative infinity




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
-1 * (pi / 0)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] -Inf
```


